VALUES
(1, 'comprehension', 'What does this rate limiter do?',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/limiter.py", "content": "import time\nfrom collections import defaultdict\n\nclass SlidingWindowLimiter:\n    def __init__(self, max_requests: int, window_seconds: int):\n        self.max_requests = max_requests\n        self.window_seconds = window_seconds\n        self._requests = defaultdict(list)\n\n    def allow(self, client_id: str) -> bool:\n        now = time.monotonic()\n        cutoff = now - self.window_seconds\n        self._requests[client_id] = [\n            t for t in self._requests[client_id] if t > cutoff\n        ]\n        if len(self._requests[client_id]) >= self.max_requests:\n            return False\n        self._requests[client_id].append(now)\n        return True\n\n    def remaining(self, client_id: str) -> int:\n        now = time.monotonic()\n        cutoff = now - self.window_seconds\n        active = [t for t in self._requests[client_id] if t > cutoff]\n        return max(0, self.max_requests - len(active))"}]}',
 'Read the SlidingWindowLimiter class and answer these questions:\n1. What algorithm does this implement? (one sentence)\n2. What happens when a client exceeds the limit?\n3. Is this implementation thread-safe? Explain why or why not.\n4. What is the time complexity of the allow() method?\n5. If max_requests=100 and window_seconds=60, and a client made 50 requests in the last 30 seconds, how many more can they make right now?',
 '{"correct_answers": ["sliding window rate limiting", "returns False / request is denied", "not thread-safe because defaultdict and list operations are not atomic", "O(n) where n is number of requests in window", "50"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['python'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

(1, 'comprehension', 'Explain this caching decorator',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/cache.py", "content": "import functools\nimport time\nimport hashlib\nimport json\n\ndef timed_cache(ttl_seconds: int = 300, maxsize: int = 128):\n    def decorator(fn):\n        cache = {}\n        order = []\n\n        @functools.wraps(fn)\n        def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n            key = hashlib.sha256(\n                json.dumps((args, sorted(kwargs.items())), default=str).encode()\n            ).hexdigest()\n            now = time.time()\n            if key in cache:\n                value, ts = cache[key]\n                if now - ts < ttl_seconds:\n                    return value\n                del cache[key]\n                order.remove(key)\n            while len(order) >= maxsize:\n                oldest = order.pop(0)\n                cache.pop(oldest, None)\n            result = fn(*args, **kwargs)\n            cache[key] = (result, now)\n            order.append(key)\n            return result\n        wrapper.cache_info = lambda: {\"size\": len(cache), \"maxsize\": maxsize, \"ttl\": ttl_seconds}\n        wrapper.cache_clear = lambda: (cache.clear(), order.clear())\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator"}]}',
 'Analyze the timed_cache decorator and answer:\n1. How does it generate cache keys? What makes two calls produce the same key?\n2. What are the two eviction strategies and when does each trigger?\n3. What bug exists in the eviction logic when a key expires AND the cache is full?\n4. What happens if the decorated function raises an exception?\n5. Why does it use SHA-256 for the key instead of just using the args tuple directly?',
 '{"correct_answers": ["SHA-256 of JSON-serialized args+kwargs", "TTL expiry and LRU when maxsize reached", "expired key is removed from cache but order.remove runs before maxsize eviction so a slot is freed unnecessarily", "exception propagates and nothing is cached", "tuples with unhashable types like dicts/lists would fail as dict keys"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['python'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

(1, 'comprehension', 'Trace the async pipeline',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/pipeline.rs", "content": "use tokio::sync::mpsc;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\npub struct Pipeline {\n    buffer_size: usize,\n}\n\nimpl Pipeline {\n    pub fn new(buffer_size: usize) -> Self {\n        Self { buffer_size }\n    }\n\n    pub async fn run(&self, input: Vec<String>) -> Vec<String> {\n        let (tx1, mut rx1) = mpsc::channel(self.buffer_size);\n        let (tx2, mut rx2) = mpsc::channel(self.buffer_size);\n        let (tx3, mut rx3) = mpsc::channel(self.buffer_size);\n\n        // Stage 1: validate\n        tokio::spawn(async move {\n            for item in input {\n                if !item.is_empty() {\n                    let _ = tx1.send(item).await;\n                }\n            }\n        });\n\n        // Stage 2: transform\n        tokio::spawn(async move {\n            while let Some(item) = rx1.recv().await {\n                let transformed = item.to_uppercase();\n                tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(10)).await;\n                let _ = tx2.send(transformed).await;\n            }\n        });\n\n        // Stage 3: deduplicate\n        tokio::spawn(async move {\n            let mut seen = std::collections::HashSet::new();\n            while let Some(item) = rx2.recv().await {\n                if seen.insert(item.clone()) {\n                    let _ = tx3.send(item).await;\n                }\n            }\n        });\n\n        // Collect\n        let mut results = Vec::new();\n        while let Some(item) = rx3.recv().await {\n            results.push(item);\n        }\n        results\n    }\n}"}]}',
 'Given input: vec!["hello", "", "world", "hello", "rust", ""], trace the pipeline and answer:\n1. What does each stage do?\n2. What is the final output vector?\n3. Why does stage 2 have a sleep? What real-world scenario does this simulate?\n4. What happens if buffer_size is 1 and stage 2 is slow — can the pipeline deadlock? Why or why not?\n5. Are the output items guaranteed to be in the same order as input? Explain.',
 '{"correct_answers": ["stage1 filters empty, stage2 uppercases, stage3 deduplicates", "[\"HELLO\", \"WORLD\", \"RUST\"]", "simulates IO-bound work like network calls or disk reads", "no deadlock because each stage consumes from previous channel before producing to next", "yes order is preserved because channels are FIFO and each stage processes sequentially"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['rust'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

-- ─── Level 1: Debugging ────────────────────────────────────────

(1, 'debugging', 'Find the off-by-one bug',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/pagination.py", "content": "def paginate(items: list, page: int, per_page: int = 20) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Return a page of items with metadata.\"\"\"\n    total = len(items)\n    total_pages = total // per_page + (1 if total % per_page else 0)\n    \n    if page < 1 or page > total_pages:\n        return {\"items\": [], \"page\": page, \"total_pages\": total_pages, \"total\": total}\n    \n    start = (page - 1) * per_page\n    end = start + per_page\n    \n    return {\n        \"items\": items[start:end],\n        \"page\": page,\n        \"total_pages\": total_pages,\n        \"total\": total,\n        \"has_next\": page < total_pages,\n        \"has_prev\": page > 0,\n    }\n\n\ndef paginate_query(query_results: list, cursor: str | None, limit: int = 20) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Cursor-based pagination.\"\"\"\n    if cursor:\n        # Find item after cursor\n        idx = next((i for i, item in enumerate(query_results) if item[\"id\"] == cursor), -1)\n        if idx == -1:\n            start = 0\n        else:\n            start = idx  # BUG: should be idx + 1\n    else:\n        start = 0\n    \n    page_items = query_results[start:start + limit]\n    next_cursor = page_items[-1][\"id\"] if page_items else None\n    \n    return {\n        \"items\": page_items,\n        \"next_cursor\": next_cursor,\n        \"has_more\": start + limit < len(query_results),\n    }"}]}',
 'This pagination module has multiple bugs. Find ALL of them:\n1. Test paginate() with exactly 20 items, per_page=20, page=1. Does has_prev return the correct value?\n2. Test paginate_query() — what happens when you paginate with a cursor that matches an existing item? Does it skip that item or include it again?\n3. What happens in paginate_query() when query_results is empty and cursor is None?\n4. What happens in paginate() when total is 0?\n\nFor each bug, state: (a) the line, (b) the current behavior, (c) the correct behavior.',
 '{"correct_answers": ["has_prev should be page > 1 not page > 0 so page 1 incorrectly shows has_prev=True", "cursor item is included again because start=idx should be start=idx+1", "page_items is empty so page_items[-1] raises IndexError", "total_pages is 0 so page=1 > 0=total_pages returns empty which is correct but edge case"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['python'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

(1, 'debugging', 'Why does this connection pool leak?',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/pool.py", "content": "import threading\nimport queue\nimport time\n\nclass ConnectionPool:\n    def __init__(self, factory, max_size=10, timeout=30):\n        self._factory = factory\n        self._max_size = max_size\n        self._timeout = timeout\n        self._pool = queue.Queue(maxsize=max_size)\n        self._size = 0\n        self._lock = threading.Lock()\n    \n    def acquire(self):\n        try:\n            conn = self._pool.get_nowait()\n            if self._is_healthy(conn):\n                return conn\n            # Unhealthy connection, create new one\n            return self._factory()\n        except queue.Empty:\n            with self._lock:\n                if self._size < self._max_size:\n                    self._size += 1\n                    return self._factory()\n            # Pool exhausted, wait\n            return self._pool.get(timeout=self._timeout)\n    \n    def release(self, conn):\n        try:\n            self._pool.put_nowait(conn)\n        except queue.Full:\n            pass  # Discard if pool is full\n    \n    def _is_healthy(self, conn):\n        try:\n            conn.ping()\n            return True\n        except Exception:\n            return False"}]}',
 'This connection pool has a resource leak. Analyze the code and answer:\n1. What is the leak? Trace the exact sequence of events that causes _size to grow but connections to disappear.\n2. Under what conditions does the leak become critical?\n3. Write a fix (pseudocode is fine) that prevents the leak.\n4. Is there a race condition in acquire()? If so, describe it.',
 '{"correct_answers": ["when unhealthy connection is discarded in acquire, _size is not decremented but a new connection is created via _factory without incrementing _size, OR when release discards due to Full _size is not decremented", "under high load with flaky connections _size reaches max but pool queue is empty", "decrement _size when discarding unhealthy connections and when release drops a connection", "yes between get_nowait and the health check another thread could also get_nowait on an empty pool"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'hard', ARRAY['python'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

-- ─── Level 1: Reasoning ────────────────────────────────────────

(1, 'reasoning', 'Predict the output of this state machine',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/fsm.py", "content": "from enum import Enum, auto\n\nclass State(Enum):\n    IDLE = auto()\n    CONNECTING = auto()\n    CONNECTED = auto()\n    RETRYING = auto()\n    FAILED = auto()\n\nclass ConnectionFSM:\n    def __init__(self, max_retries=3):\n        self.state = State.IDLE\n        self.retries = 0\n        self.max_retries = max_retries\n        self.log = []\n    \n    def connect(self):\n        if self.state in (State.IDLE, State.RETRYING):\n            self.state = State.CONNECTING\n            self.log.append(f\"connecting (attempt {self.retries + 1})\")\n    \n    def on_success(self):\n        if self.state == State.CONNECTING:\n            self.state = State.CONNECTED\n            self.retries = 0\n            self.log.append(\"connected\")\n    \n    def on_failure(self):\n        if self.state == State.CONNECTING:\n            self.retries += 1\n            if self.retries >= self.max_retries:\n                self.state = State.FAILED\n                self.log.append(f\"failed after {self.retries} attempts\")\n            else:\n                self.state = State.RETRYING\n                self.log.append(f\"retry {self.retries}/{self.max_retries}\")\n    \n    def disconnect(self):\n        if self.state == State.CONNECTED:\n            self.state = State.IDLE\n            self.log.append(\"disconnected\")\n\nfsm = ConnectionFSM(max_retries=3)\nfsm.connect()\nfsm.on_failure()\nfsm.connect()\nfsm.on_failure()\nfsm.connect()\nfsm.on_success()\nfsm.disconnect()\nfsm.connect()\nfsm.on_failure()\nfsm.on_failure()  # What happens here?\nfsm.connect()     # And here?"}]}',
 'Trace the execution of the ConnectionFSM step by step. For each method call, state:\n1. The state BEFORE the call\n2. The state AFTER the call\n3. What gets appended to self.log (if anything)\n\nThen answer: What is the final state? What is the complete log list? What happens at the last on_failure() and connect() calls — do they have any effect?',
 '{"correct_answers": ["final state is RETRYING", "log is [connecting (attempt 1), retry 1/3, connecting (attempt 2), retry 2/3, connecting (attempt 3), connected, disconnected, connecting (attempt 1), retry 1/3]", "second on_failure has no effect because state is RETRYING not CONNECTING", "last connect transitions from RETRYING to CONNECTING"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['python'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

(1, 'reasoning', 'What will this concurrent code print?',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/channels.go", "content": "package main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"sync\"\n\t\"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\tch := make(chan int, 3)\n\tvar wg sync.WaitGroup\n\tresults := make([]string, 0)\n\tvar mu sync.Mutex\n\n\t// Producer\n\twg.Add(1)\n\tgo func() {\n\t\tdefer wg.Done()\n\t\tfor i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {\n\t\t\tch <- i\n\t\t\tmu.Lock()\n\t\t\tresults = append(results, fmt.Sprintf(\"sent:%d\", i))\n\t\t\tmu.Unlock()\n\t\t}\n\t\tclose(ch)\n\t}()\n\n\t// Consumer\n\twg.Add(1)\n\tgo func() {\n\t\tdefer wg.Done()\n\t\ttime.Sleep(50 * time.Millisecond)\n\t\tfor v := range ch {\n\t\t\tmu.Lock()\n\t\t\tresults = append(results, fmt.Sprintf(\"recv:%d\", v))\n\t\t\tmu.Unlock()\n\t\t}\n\t}()\n\n\twg.Wait()\n\tfor _, r := range results {\n\t\tfmt.Println(r)\n\t}\n}"}]}',
 'Analyze this Go concurrent program:\n1. The channel has buffer size 3. The producer sends 5 items. The consumer sleeps 50ms before starting. Explain what happens — when does the producer block?\n2. What are the first 3 entries guaranteed to be in results? Why?\n3. Is the final order of results deterministic? Explain.\n4. What would change if the channel was unbuffered (make(chan int))?\n5. What would happen if close(ch) was removed?',
 '{"correct_answers": ["producer sends 1,2,3 into buffer without blocking then blocks on send 4 until consumer starts reading", "first 3 are sent:1 sent:2 sent:3 because buffer allows 3 sends before consumer wakes", "partially deterministic - first 3 sends happen before any recv but after that interleaving varies", "producer would block on first send until consumer reads so sends and recvs would alternate", "consumer would block forever on range ch waiting for channel close causing goroutine leak and deadlock"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['go'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

