(1, 'debugging', 'Find the SQL injection vulnerability',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/search.py", "content": "import sqlite3\n\ndef search_users(db_path: str, query: str, role: str = None) -> list:\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(db_path)\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    \n    sql = f\"SELECT id, name, email FROM users WHERE name LIKE ''%{query}%''\"\n    if role:\n        sql += f\" AND role = ''{role}''\"\n    sql += \" ORDER BY name LIMIT 50\"\n    \n    cursor.execute(sql)\n    results = cursor.fetchall()\n    conn.close()\n    return results\n\ndef get_user_by_id(db_path: str, user_id: int) -> dict:\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(db_path)\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    cursor.execute(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?\", (user_id,))\n    row = cursor.fetchone()\n    conn.close()\n    if row:\n        return {\"id\": row[0], \"name\": row[1], \"email\": row[2]}\n    return None"}]}',
 'Analyze this code for security vulnerabilities:\n1. Identify ALL SQL injection vulnerabilities. For each, show an example malicious input.\n2. Which function is safe and why?\n3. Write a fixed version of the vulnerable function using parameterized queries.\n4. Besides SQL injection, what other issue exists with the connection handling?\n5. Could an attacker use the vulnerable function to extract data from other tables? Show how.',
 '{"correct_answers": ["search_users has SQL injection via both query and role parameters using f-string interpolation", "get_user_by_id is safe because it uses parameterized query with ? placeholder", "use cursor.execute with ? placeholders and pass query/role as parameters", "connection is not closed if an exception occurs - should use context manager or try/finally", "yes using UNION SELECT: query = \"'' UNION SELECT sql,2,3 FROM sqlite_master--\" extracts schema"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['python'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform'),

(1, 'reasoning', 'Predict the memory behavior',
 '{"files": [{"path": "src/cache.ts", "content": "class LRUCache<K, V> {\n  private map = new Map<K, V>();\n  private readonly maxSize: number;\n\n  constructor(maxSize: number) {\n    this.maxSize = maxSize;\n  }\n\n  get(key: K): V | undefined {\n    const value = this.map.get(key);\n    if (value !== undefined) {\n      // Move to end (most recently used)\n      this.map.delete(key);\n      this.map.set(key, value);\n    }\n    return value;\n  }\n\n  set(key: K, value: V): void {\n    if (this.map.has(key)) {\n      this.map.delete(key);\n    }\n    this.map.set(key, value);\n    if (this.map.size > this.maxSize) {\n      // Delete oldest (first) entry\n      const firstKey = this.map.keys().next().value!;\n      this.map.delete(firstKey);\n    }\n  }\n\n  get size(): number {\n    return this.map.size;\n  }\n}\n\nconst cache = new LRUCache<string, number>(3);\ncache.set(\"a\", 1);\ncache.set(\"b\", 2);\ncache.set(\"c\", 3);\ncache.get(\"a\");\ncache.set(\"d\", 4);\ncache.get(\"c\");\ncache.set(\"e\", 5);"}]}',
 'Trace the LRU cache operations step by step:\n1. After each operation, list the Map contents in insertion order (oldest to newest).\n2. What is the final state of the cache?\n3. Why does JavaScript Map preserve insertion order and how does this implementation exploit that?\n4. What is the time complexity of get() and set()? Is this optimal for an LRU cache?\n5. What would happen if get() returned the value WITHOUT the delete+re-insert?',
 '{"correct_answers": ["final state: a=1, d=4 evicted... cache contains c=3, d=4 wait let me retrace... after set a,b,c: [a,b,c]. get a: [b,c,a]. set d: [c,a,d] (b evicted). get c: [a,d,c]. set e: [d,c,e] (a evicted)", "final cache is {d:4, c:3, e:5}", "Map preserves insertion order per ES2015 spec so first key is always the oldest/least recently used making eviction O(1)", "get is O(1) amortized and set is O(1) amortized - this is optimal", "without delete+re-insert get would not update recency so frequently accessed items could be evicted as if they were old"], "partial_credit": true}',
 'standard', ARRAY['typescript'], '2026-04-01', '2026-07-01', 'platform');
